Ubicumque resolutus fueris, quaecumque te materia destrux- erit, hauserit, aboleverit, in nihilum prodegerit, reddet te. Ejus est nihilum ipsum, cujus et totum. Ergo, inquitis, semper moriendum erit, et semper resur- 5 gendum. Si ita rerum Dominus destinasset, ingratis expe- rireris conditionis tuae legem. At nunc non aliter destinavit, quam praedicavit. 4. Ergo, inquitis, semper moriendum erit. Ergo looks back to the analogies addueed from Nature in the passage above ‘ Lux quo- tidie,’ ete. They imply, it is said, a recurrence of deaths and resurrec- tions. Tertullian tacitly admitti, but passes by the objection; these analogies (he would reply) are illustrations, not arguments. See Kaye‚ p. 258.
